				Have you ever opened an expensive box of chocolates? </p>

<p class="benefit">First there's searching for the pull-strip that goes around the pack so that you can tear open the cellophane in one quick motion. Then, gently pulling at cardboard lid until you feel the tabs holding it down start to give. Usually there's a layer of light corrugated card to lift up, underneath which each chocolate sits in its own unique shape on the carefully moulded tray. Some chocolates are individually wrapped in foil, each embossed with their own patterns, and of course there's the little instruction booklet too. </p>

<p class="benefit">All of these things add to the pleasure of eating the chocolate&mdash;it's very different than putting your fingers into a bag of minstrels. </p>

<p class="benefit">It's both a tactile and visual experience which delights your senses, and the box itself is as important as the chocolates.</p>

<p class="benefit">Wouldn't it be great if your guests could feel the same delight when opening your invitations?</p>

<p class="benefit">It's that feeling we, of anticipation and delight, that we set about to create with our invitations&hellip;</p>
