				</div>


<p class="benefit">Not to mention the delicate, frosted vellum cover, again watermarked with your monogram in a matching design, that evokes a feeling of exclusivity than card alone cannot match.</p>

<p class="benefit">And the pièce de résistance: the beautifully printed tissue paper, light as a feather, used to separate any inserts such as RSVP cards or information sheets that may be enclosed with your invitation. If you opt for a box envelope (read more in a bit...) then these are layered either side of your invitation card: it really does feel like opening a box containing an expensive pair of designer shoes. </p>

<p class="benefit">And not only does the tissue paper add an angelic beauty, it also serves the practical function of preventing the ink imprinting during transit. </p>

<p class="benefit">But to really know a good invitation, you need to know what makes a bad invitation. </p>

<p class="benefit">So let's take a look at some of the biggest mistakes&hellip;</p>



